TY  - JOUR
AU  - Kim, Myung Jig
AU  - Nelson, Charles R.
AU  - Startz, Richard
T1  - Mean Reversion in Stock Prices? A Reappraisal of the Empirical Evidence
PY  - 1991
Y1  - 1991/05/01
DO  - 10.2307/2298009
JO  - The Review of Economic Studies
JA  - Rev Econ Stud
VL  - 58
IS  - 3
SP  - 515
EP  - 528
SN  - 0034-6527
AB  - The paper re-examines the empirical evidence for mean-reverting behaviour in stock prices. Comparison of data before and after World War II shows that mean reversion is entirely a pre-war phenomenon. Using randomization methods to calculate significance levels, we find that the full sample evidence for mean reversion is weaker than previously indicated by Monte Carlo methods under a Normal assumption. Further, the switch to mean-averting behaviour after the war is about to be too strong to be compatible with sampling variation. We interpret these findings as evidence of a fundamental change in the stock returns process and conjecture that it may be due to the resolution of the uncertainties of the 1930's and 1940's.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.2307/2298009
ER  - 



